{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b93b86f1-dc5e-40b7-8ecd-2afd284b5475","content":"On macOS, you have two main options:\n\n### 1. macOS Crash Reports (automatic)\nmacOS generates crash reports automatically. Look in:\n```bash\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. You can also browse them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n### 2. Core Dumps (manual opt-in)\nEnable core dumps before running your app:\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\nsudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n```\nCore files are written to `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n> **Tip:** The `.ips` crash reports are often sufficient — they include the faulting thread, stack traces, and register state. For deeper debugging with `lldb`, grab the core dump from `/cores/`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"22d691c5-3ff0-43a9-a868-7bf59186b227","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's where to find them:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user-level crashes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level crashes).\n\n2. You can also use **Console.app** to browse them.\n\n3. Core dumps can be enabled via `ulimit -c unlimited`, and they go to `/cores/`.\n\n\nI'll keep this straightforward and practical.","outputTokens":420,"requestId":"7852:13DD23:4B3398:56A835:69FA9DC0"},"id":"8c6b4dd9-d184-4e2d-a403-a08a4b57f559","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:54.358Z","parentId":"462b13fa-68a5-4aaa-b050-40f125174039"}
